I recently had some one tell me that being a death doula is not a thing. That it's hospice. 

"Ma'am you're very sweet but no." 

We are an addition to hospice but we are not hospice. And not all hospice care is the same. Especially, if your "young." 

She looked at me like I was crazy. I said "ma'am most of my virtual transitional clients last year were between the ages of 27 and 44.
Some were covered thru medical or private insurance and others had family and friends pitch in to cover end of life care and expenses. I gave my services for free. 

And as a ancestral death doula I don't just work with physical death. I work with Living, Energetic and Spiritual death as well." 

She was too stunned to speak. 

The modern version of a death doula is a transitional doula but an ancestral death doula is the medicine woman (person) of their village. They embrace all deaths. 

As a people we used to be very close with death and now some of us are returning to our roots and embracing the death bed call. 

So what kind of death doula are you? Or what kind of death doula would you like to be? 

Death Doula workshop coming back in September. 

Much Love ‚ù§Ô∏èüíÄü¶ã
Jess

Death is the shadow on the face of life,
for the opposite of death is birth, not life;
that which is born must die.

Life has no opposite, for life goes on;
only its forms must change unceasingly.

It is life which creates, uses and then destroys
each form of life, whether yours or mine
or that of the mountain, the empire or the fly.
-
The fear of death
is the fear of the end of an illusion;
so long as the illusion persists
so long will the fear remain.
-
Christmas Humphreys,
The Buddhist Way Of Life

What do you think of a casket made from mushrooms? Loop Biotech collaborates with nature to create a completely biodegradable casket that breaks down within 48 days. 

The Loop caskets are made in The Netherlands and are certified to be used for traditional and natural burial, as well as cremations. 

‚ÄúWhile most researchers had their eyes on the plants and organisms above ground, recent discoveries show that earth‚Äôs most crucial creatures live underneath us. Mycelium, the underground root network of mushrooms, are known as nature‚Äôs biggest recyclers. The unique power of mycelium is its ability to share nutrients, communicate with the forest floor, and enhance soil quality. Its power to transform dead organic matter into new life makes this organism the driving force in nature‚Äôs cycle of life.‚Äù

Reflecting on End Well 2024: Transforming Conversations Around Grief and Loss

The End Well conference, founded by Dr. Shoshana Ungerleider, once again brought together thought leaders, innovators, and advocates to tackle one of life‚Äôs biggest challenges: how we navigate grief, loss, death, and dying. Held earlier this year, the event reminded us why conversations around end-of-life care, palliative medicine, and mental health are more critical than ever.

For too long, our society has avoided discussing grief and the realities of death, leaving many to navigate these experiences in silence. End Well challenges that norm, breaking down stigma and helping us create a culture where loss is acknowledged and healing can thrive. This year‚Äôs speakers brought powerful stories, insights, and solutions to the table, inspiring us to rethink what it means to truly ‚Äúend well.‚Äù

In the shadows of the death and dying industry, where compassion meets mortality, lies an often-overlooked narrative of dedication.

A key group of unsung heroes, guardians of the grim if you will‚Äîthe caregivers, hospice workers, funeral directors, and diverse other professionals who navigate the deep waters of death every day. 

Yet, within their honorable work, a silent epidemic looms: burnout. 

In their tireless commitment to easing the transfer from this life to the next lies a tale of extraordinary resilience. 

These amazing individuals face daunting challenges that threaten their well-being yet they continue to serve, undeterred by the demands of their work.

Why Are We So Afraid to Talk About Palliative Care?

A viral video by @drjrubinstein highlights an uncomfortable truth: many people and even healthcare providers resist the idea of palliative care. Why? Because it forces us to confront mortality, grief, and the realities of serious illness‚Äîtopics we often avoid.

Palliative care isn‚Äôt about giving up; it‚Äôs about living as fully and comfortably as possible during life‚Äôs most challenging moments. It offers support, dignity, and relief, yet the stigma around death and dying often prevents us from embracing this compassionate form of care.

We need to change the narrative. Talking about death doesn‚Äôt make it come faster‚Äîit makes it more meaningful. Let‚Äôs normalize these conversations, for ourselves, our families, and our communities.

Thank you, @drjrubinstein, for opening the door to this vital discussion.

"Losing a beloved pet leaves a void that‚Äôs often hard to put into words," writes Phil Benavides, INELDA-trained doula and founder of Remembrance @remembrancepets. "It can be overwhelming to navigate their absence, but honoring their life and the love shared is a powerful and essential step in healing. I decided, with my partners, to create Remembrance to celebrate these lives with empathy, backed by science. We developed a 3-D digital memorial platform using augmented reality and artificial intelligence to provide a space where memories can be kept alive and revisited anytime, from anywhere in the world."

Read Phil's article where he shares the about the science of grief, healing through movement and embracing your own journey of remembrance through our link in bio @inelda_doulas
